title.children: ASIC sues AustralianSuper over 'failure' that took $69m from the accounts of 90,000 members, ASX down

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: AustralianSuper is firmly in the spotlight today with the corporate regulator ASIC taking it to court over claims it failed to consolidate the superannuation accounts of 90,000 members over a 10-year period, costing them $69 million. The superannuation fund, which is Australia's largest, self-reported the issue, but ASIC alleges they were not notified until 2021 even though the issue was first detected in 2018. AustralianSuper is also in the process of finalising the repayments of $69 million to the accounts. ASIC deputy chair Sarah Court says the superannuation fund clearly didn't act in the best interest of its members, and will have a long-term impact on their superannuation balances. You can watch her full chat with finance presenter Sue Lannin below:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ASIC's deputy chair, Sarah Court, told The World Today that the corporate regulator's legal action against AustralianSuper should serve as a reminder for all super funds to ensure they have the right systems in place to deal with duplicate accounts held by members. "The important point here for the whole of the superannuation industry, not just AustralianSuper, but more broadly, is that all trustees have got to have the systems and processes in place to make sure that they are detecting where there are multiple accounts held by their members, and where it's in the members best interest to get those accounts amalgamated ," she told the ABC's senior business correspondent Peter Ryan. "And the reason for that, of course, is it prevents members paying double, triple the fees, insurance premiums and the like going forward, which of course can have significant impacts over time on their superannuation balances ."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's been a big fortnight of headlines for Qantas, and the scandals have had a major impact on the company's share price — and its value (or market capitalisation) — as a result. Four weeks ago on August 11, the airline's share price closed at $6.49, giving it a value of $11.2 billion, based on the total number of shares issued (which is around 1.7 billion ). At the close of trade yesterday, its share price was almost a full dollar lower, at $5.57. That's a fall in the airline's share price of 15% between August 11 and September 7. Based on yesterday's closing price, Qantas is currently worth around $9.6 billion — meaning it has shed around $1.5 billion or just under 2% from its value in the past four weeks. Right now, its shares are about 0.3% lower at $5.53.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Qantas sheds $1.5 billion in value in the last four weeks
